1. HTML Architecture (Structure)
    
    <!DOCTYPE html>: Declares the document type as HTML5 so the web browser knows how to render the code.

    <meta name="viewport">: Instructs mobile devices to scale the webpage correctly according to the physical screen width.

    <canvas id="network-canvas">: Creates an invisible, empty drawing box on the screen. The JavaScript later takes 
                                control of this box to draw the moving particles.

    class="..." and id="...": Identifiers applied to HTML tags. IDs are unique to a single element; 
                            classes are applied to multiple elements that share the same styling.

    <div class="terminal-container">: A generic structural container used to group the typewriter text elements together.

    data-target="...": A custom attribute created by the developer to store an invisible number (0, 1, 2).
                    The JavaScript reads this number to know which slider panel to display when a specific button is clicked.

    <svg>: Scalable Vector Graphics. It allows the browser to draw high-quality icons using mathematical
        coordinates written directly in the HTML, avoiding the need to load external image files.

2. JavaScript Engine (Logic & Automation)
Note: This file uses zero external libraries. Everything relies on native browser APIs (Application Programming Interfaces).

    Native Browser APIs Used:

    Promise: An object that represents a task that will finish at some point in the future. It prevents the code from freezing while waiting for a delay.

    IntersectionObserver: A browser tool that constantly watches specific HTML elements to see if they have entered 
                        the user's visible screen. It is used here to trigger animations only when the user scrolls down.

    fetch(): A network protocol tool that securely contacts the external GitHub server to ask for the repository data.

    requestAnimationFrame(): A high-performance timer that tells the browser to run the physics drawing loop exactly in sync with 
                            the monitor's refresh rate (usually 60 times per second).

    Custom Functions & Definitions:

    sleep(ms): A custom utility function that forces the script to pause execution for a specific number of milliseconds.

    typeLine(elementId, text, speed): An asynchronous function that takes a text string, splits it into individual letters, 
                                    and injects them into the HTML one by one to fake a typing effect.

    runTypewriterSequence(): The master controller function that organizes the typeLine animations in chronological order using await commands.

    observeStaticCards(): A function that attaches the IntersectionObserver to the project cards. When the cards scroll into view, 
                        the observer adds a CSS class (show) that triggers the fade-in animation.

    fetchGitHubProjects(): An asynchronous function that contacts the GitHub API, downloads the JSON data, filters out 
                        the unwanted repositories, converts the remaining data into raw HTML text, and injects that text into the webpage.

    initTabSlider(): A function that listens for clicks on the navigation buttons. When clicked, it calculates a mathematical percentage 
                    (like -25% or -50%) and shifts the slider track sideways.

    class Node: A blueprint that defines what a "particle" is. It holds the particle's current X/Y coordinates on the screen, its speed, and its color.

    Node.update(): A logic method inside the Node class. It calculates where the particle should move on the next frame, 
                makes it bounce if it hits the edge of the screen, and pushes it away if the user's mouse gets too close.

    animate(): A recursive loop function. It wipes the <canvas> completely clean, asks every particle to update its position, redraws the particles, 
            and draws lines between them if they are close enough.

3. CSS Architecture (Styling & Physics)

    :root: A global storage area at the top of the CSS file. It holds custom variables (like --bg-color: #0d1117;). 
        If the background color needs to change, it only has to be changed here, and the entire site updates automatically.

    * { box-sizing: border-box; }: A universal reset. It forces the browser to include padding and borders in the final width calculation of an element, 
                                preventing the layout from accidentally breaking or stretching.

    pointer-events: none;: A rule applied to the <canvas>. It makes the canvas physically unclickable, ensuring the user's mouse clicks pass 
                        straight through the animation to hit the buttons underneath.

    display: flex;: A layout tool that aligns child elements perfectly in a row or column, automatically spacing them out.

    display: grid;: A layout tool that builds a two-dimensional grid. It is used here to create the 3-column project layout 
                    that automatically collapses into 1 column on mobile phones.

    transform: translateY(30px);: A spatial positioning rule. It forces the project cards to start 30 pixels lower than their normal position. 
                                When combined with opacity: 0, it creates the starting state for the slide-up animation.

    transition: all 0.3s ease;: An animation rule that tells the browser to smoothly calculate the difference between states over 0.3 seconds. 
                                For example, when a button is hovered, this makes the color change fade in rather than snap instantly.

    @keyframes: The blueprint for a continuous CSS animation. It defines the start (0%), middle (50%), and end (100%) states of an effect,
                such as the glowing cursor blinking.